& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The advent and implementation of digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) have had a significant effect on breast cancer detection and image-guided breast procedures. DBT has been shown to improve the visualization of architectural distortions and noncalcified masses. With the incorporation of DBT imaging, biopsy of those findings seen only with DBT is feasible, and the need for localization and surgical excision to determine the pathologic diagnosis is avoided. The additional benefits of reduced procedural time, better localization, and increased technical success support the use of DBT for breast biopsy. DBT-guided biopsy can be performed with the patient prone or upright, depending on the table or unit used. Upright positioning enables improved patient comfort, particularly in patients who have restricted mobility, weight-related limitations, and/or difficulty lying prone for an extended period. Upright DBT-guided breast procedures require a cohesive team approach with overlapping radiologist and technologist responsibilities. Since this is a common breast procedure, the radiologist should be familiar with preprocedural considerations, patient preparations, and use of the biopsy equipment. The basic principles of upright DBT-guided breast biopsy are described in this comprehensive review. The various procedural components, including alternative approaches and techniques, are discussed. Tips and tricks for navigating the biopsy procedure to minimize complications, imaging examples of crucial steps, and supporting diagrams are provided. In addition, the challenges of performing upright DBT-guided biopsy, with troubleshooting techniques to ensure a successful procedure, are reviewed.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210017">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210017">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagram illustrates the difference in notch size between standard and petite digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) biopsy devices. The petite device is preferred for patients with thin (thickness ≤3 cm) breasts, a negative stroke margin, and superficial breast lesions."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig1.jpeg" height="1266" width="3200" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Diagram illustrates the difference in notch size between standard and petite digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) biopsy devices. The petite device is preferred for patients with thin (thickness ≤3 cm) breasts, a negative stroke margin, and superficial breast lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Selection of the biopsy approach. Full mediolateral (a) and craniocaudal (b) mammograms show the distance from the skin to the target, which is a group of amorphous calcifications (circle) in this case. A superior biopsy approach was selected on the basis of the shortest distance from the skin to the target."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig2a.jpeg" height="2246" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Selection of the biopsy approach. Full mediolateral <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammograms show the distance from the skin to the target, which is a group of amorphous calcifications (circle) in this case. A superior biopsy approach was selected on the basis of the shortest distance from the skin to the target.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Selection of the biopsy approach. Full mediolateral (a) and craniocaudal (b) mammograms show the distance from the skin to the target, which is a group of amorphous calcifications (circle) in this case. A superior biopsy approach was selected on the basis of the shortest distance from the skin to the target."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig2b.jpeg" height="2246" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Selection of the biopsy approach. Full mediolateral <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammograms show the distance from the skin to the target, which is a group of amorphous calcifications (circle) in this case. A superior biopsy approach was selected on the basis of the shortest distance from the skin to the target.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Photograph shows biopsy team members (radiologist, technologist, and patient) during the time-out, which is performed to verify the examination to be performed and confirm the patient information in or on the consent form, wrist band, mammography unit, and paper or electronic patient chart."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig3.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Photograph shows biopsy team members (radiologist, technologist, and patient) during the time-out, which is performed to verify the examination to be performed and confirm the patient information in or on the consent form, wrist band, mammography unit, and paper or electronic patient chart.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Photograph of DBT-guided biopsy tray. The tray components include (from left to right) sterile towels and 4 × 4 gauze pads, lidocaine with epinephrine (for use with the biopsy device), forceps, a specimen container, a needle holder, a scalpel, a syringe containing lidocaine with epinephrine, a short-needle syringe containing lidocaine, and skin preparation solution. Additional items may be needed, depending on the biopsy device used."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig4.jpeg" height="1555" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Photograph of DBT-guided biopsy tray. The tray components include (from left to right) sterile towels and 4 × 4 gauze pads, lidocaine with epinephrine (for use with the biopsy device), forceps, a specimen container, a needle holder, a scalpel, a syringe containing lidocaine with epinephrine, a short-needle syringe containing lidocaine, and skin preparation solution. Additional items may be needed, depending on the biopsy device used.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Lateral decubitus positioning. Photograph shows a patient placed in the right lateral decubitus position to approach the left breast target inferiorly or from below. The patient is lying close to the edge of the bed and draping her arm over the image detector for improved comfort. The biopsy paddle window allows needle access to the inferior breast tissue."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig5.jpeg" height="2680" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Lateral decubitus positioning. Photograph shows a patient placed in the right lateral decubitus position to approach the left breast target inferiorly or from below. The patient is lying close to the edge of the bed and draping her arm over the image detector for improved comfort. The biopsy paddle window allows needle access to the inferior breast tissue.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Upright positioning. Photograph shows the technologist positioning the patient’s breast on the platform and confirming adequate compression. A back pillow is placed for patient comfort and to help access the posterior breast tissue. The corner of the biopsy window can be marked on the patient’s skin to indicate any movement during the procedure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig6.jpeg" height="2377" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Upright positioning. Photograph shows the technologist positioning the patient’s breast on the platform and confirming adequate compression. A back pillow is placed for patient comfort and to help access the posterior breast tissue. The corner of the biopsy window can be marked on the patient’s skin to indicate any movement during the procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Compression biopsy paddles. Photograph shows the three types of paddles used at our institution. The axillary biopsy paddle (left) has a smaller compression area with a 5.4 × 5.2-cm biopsy opening. The small paddle (middle) has a 5.4 × 5.2-cm opening, and the large paddle (right) has a 7.4 × 6.2-cm opening."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig7.jpeg" height="1772" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Compression biopsy paddles. Photograph shows the three types of paddles used at our institution. The axillary biopsy paddle (left) has a smaller compression area with a 5.4 × 5.2-cm biopsy opening. The small paddle (middle) has a 5.4 × 5.2-cm opening, and the large paddle (right) has a 7.4 × 6.2-cm opening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="(a) Scout two-dimensional (2D) lateromedial mammogram findings confirm the targeted calcifications (circle) in the paddle window. (b) Subsequently obtained three-dimensional (3D) lateromedial mammogram shows the selected tomosynthesis section on which the calcifications are best defined."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig8a.jpeg" height="1813" width="1334" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. <b>(a)</b> Scout two-dimensional (2D) lateromedial mammogram findings confirm the targeted calcifications (circle) in the paddle window. <b>(b)</b> Subsequently obtained three-dimensional (3D) lateromedial mammogram shows the selected tomosynthesis section on which the calcifications are best defined.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="(a) Scout two-dimensional (2D) lateromedial mammogram findings confirm the targeted calcifications (circle) in the paddle window. (b) Subsequently obtained three-dimensional (3D) lateromedial mammogram shows the selected tomosynthesis section on which the calcifications are best defined."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig8b.jpeg" height="1813" width="1317" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. <b>(a)</b> Scout two-dimensional (2D) lateromedial mammogram findings confirm the targeted calcifications (circle) in the paddle window. <b>(b)</b> Subsequently obtained three-dimensional (3D) lateromedial mammogram shows the selected tomosynthesis section on which the calcifications are best defined.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Targeting parameters. Diagram shows the key parameters to consider before and after firing the biopsy device. The stroke is the distance between the needle tip position before and this position after the biopsy device is fired, and is measured along the firing axis. The stroke margin is the safety margin that remains between the fired needle position and the breast platform. The radiologist should ensure that the detector plate is not damaged and the biopsy trough is seated below the skin surface."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig9.jpeg" height="2457" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Targeting parameters. Diagram shows the key parameters to consider before and after firing the biopsy device. The stroke is the distance between the needle tip position before and this position after the biopsy device is fired, and is measured along the firing axis. The stroke margin is the safety margin that remains between the fired needle position and the breast platform. The radiologist should ensure that the detector plate is not damaged and the biopsy trough is seated below the skin surface.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Technique for administering local anesthesia. (a) Photograph of superficial anesthesia being administered by placing the needle tip just deep to the skin and creating a skin wheel. (b) Photograph of deeper anesthesia being administered: The numbing needle is introduced at the angle of the biopsy needle, and anesthetic is injected while the needle is advanced to the biopsy site."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig10a.jpeg" height="1852" width="1310" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Technique for administering local anesthesia. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of superficial anesthesia being administered by placing the needle tip just deep to the skin and creating a skin wheel. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of deeper anesthesia being administered: The numbing needle is introduced at the angle of the biopsy needle, and anesthetic is injected while the needle is advanced to the biopsy site.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Technique for administering local anesthesia. (a) Photograph of superficial anesthesia being administered by placing the needle tip just deep to the skin and creating a skin wheel. (b) Photograph of deeper anesthesia being administered: The numbing needle is introduced at the angle of the biopsy needle, and anesthetic is injected while the needle is advanced to the biopsy site."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig10b.jpeg" height="1852" width="1341" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Technique for administering local anesthesia. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of superficial anesthesia being administered by placing the needle tip just deep to the skin and creating a skin wheel. <b>(b)</b> Photograph of deeper anesthesia being administered: The numbing needle is introduced at the angle of the biopsy needle, and anesthetic is injected while the needle is advanced to the biopsy site.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagram depicts the biopsy needle before and after it is fired. The target, in this case calcifications, should be located within the notch in the postfire position. The throw is the distance the needle moves once it is fired. The dead space is the distance between the distal trough and the needle tip."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig11.jpeg" height="1391" width="3200" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Diagram depicts the biopsy needle before and after it is fired. The target, in this case calcifications, should be located within the notch in the postfire position. The throw is the distance the needle moves once it is fired. The dead space is the distance between the distal trough and the needle tip.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Clock-face notation and biopsy needle. (a) Drawing depicts the inner cannula of the vacuum-assisted biopsy needle. The cannula rotates 360° for circumferential tissue sampling. The direction of the inner cannula can be controlled by a thumb wheel at the end of the device. The demarcation of the position of the biopsy aperture and clock face is located at the middle section of the device. (b) Drawing depicts a lateromedial approach for inserting the biopsy needle. Note that the 12-o’clock position is directed toward the chest wall, and the 6-o’clock position is directed toward the nipple. These clock faces are the same regardless of the approach selected."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig12a.jpeg" height="1961" width="1405" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Clock-face notation and biopsy needle. <b>(a)</b> Drawing depicts the inner cannula of the vacuum-assisted biopsy needle. The cannula rotates 360° for circumferential tissue sampling. The direction of the inner cannula can be controlled by a thumb wheel at the end of the device. The demarcation of the position of the biopsy aperture and clock face is located at the middle section of the device. <b>(b)</b> Drawing depicts a lateromedial approach for inserting the biopsy needle. Note that the 12-o’clock position is directed toward the chest wall, and the 6-o’clock position is directed toward the nipple. These clock faces are the same regardless of the approach selected.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Clock-face notation and biopsy needle. (a) Drawing depicts the inner cannula of the vacuum-assisted biopsy needle. The cannula rotates 360° for circumferential tissue sampling. The direction of the inner cannula can be controlled by a thumb wheel at the end of the device. The demarcation of the position of the biopsy aperture and clock face is located at the middle section of the device. (b) Drawing depicts a lateromedial approach for inserting the biopsy needle. Note that the 12-o’clock position is directed toward the chest wall, and the 6-o’clock position is directed toward the nipple. These clock faces are the same regardless of the approach selected."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig12b.jpeg" height="1961" width="1746" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Clock-face notation and biopsy needle. <b>(a)</b> Drawing depicts the inner cannula of the vacuum-assisted biopsy needle. The cannula rotates 360° for circumferential tissue sampling. The direction of the inner cannula can be controlled by a thumb wheel at the end of the device. The demarcation of the position of the biopsy aperture and clock face is located at the middle section of the device. <b>(b)</b> Drawing depicts a lateromedial approach for inserting the biopsy needle. Note that the 12-o’clock position is directed toward the chest wall, and the 6-o’clock position is directed toward the nipple. These clock faces are the same regardless of the approach selected.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Foot pedal. Photograph shows a foot pedal used for sampling at our institution. In some practices, a button on the biopsy device or a separate remote may be used."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig13.jpeg" height="1076" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Foot pedal. Photograph shows a foot pedal used for sampling at our institution. In some practices, a button on the biopsy device or a separate remote may be used.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Photographs show the specimen collection instruments and process. (a) The instruments used for specimen collection include a plastic tray (white arrow) on which to place the tissue collected from the biopsy device, a white cassette (black arrow) in which to place target samples, a hemostat (green arrow) to spread apart sample pieces, and a formalin container (*) to send samples to the pathology department. (b) The specimen is routinely imaged to confirm adequate sampling of the target. (c) The specimen radiograph can help determine which specific tissue cores (circles), in this case calcifications, to place in the cassette."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig14a.jpeg" height="1711" width="1269" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Photographs show the specimen collection instruments and process. <b>(a)</b> The instruments used for specimen collection include a plastic tray (white arrow) on which to place the tissue collected from the biopsy device, a white cassette (black arrow) in which to place target samples, a hemostat (green arrow) to spread apart sample pieces, and a formalin container (*) to send samples to the pathology department. <b>(b)</b> The specimen is routinely imaged to confirm adequate sampling of the target. <b>(c)</b> The specimen radiograph can help determine which specific tissue cores (circles), in this case calcifications, to place in the cassette.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Photographs show the specimen collection instruments and process. (a) The instruments used for specimen collection include a plastic tray (white arrow) on which to place the tissue collected from the biopsy device, a white cassette (black arrow) in which to place target samples, a hemostat (green arrow) to spread apart sample pieces, and a formalin container (*) to send samples to the pathology department. (b) The specimen is routinely imaged to confirm adequate sampling of the target. (c) The specimen radiograph can help determine which specific tissue cores (circles), in this case calcifications, to place in the cassette."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig14b.jpeg" height="1711" width="1313" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Photographs show the specimen collection instruments and process. <b>(a)</b> The instruments used for specimen collection include a plastic tray (white arrow) on which to place the tissue collected from the biopsy device, a white cassette (black arrow) in which to place target samples, a hemostat (green arrow) to spread apart sample pieces, and a formalin container (*) to send samples to the pathology department. <b>(b)</b> The specimen is routinely imaged to confirm adequate sampling of the target. <b>(c)</b> The specimen radiograph can help determine which specific tissue cores (circles), in this case calcifications, to place in the cassette.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Photographs show the specimen collection instruments and process. (a) The instruments used for specimen collection include a plastic tray (white arrow) on which to place the tissue collected from the biopsy device, a white cassette (black arrow) in which to place target samples, a hemostat (green arrow) to spread apart sample pieces, and a formalin container (*) to send samples to the pathology department. (b) The specimen is routinely imaged to confirm adequate sampling of the target. (c) The specimen radiograph can help determine which specific tissue cores (circles), in this case calcifications, to place in the cassette."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig14c.jpeg" height="1711" width="1119" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Photographs show the specimen collection instruments and process. <b>(a)</b> The instruments used for specimen collection include a plastic tray (white arrow) on which to place the tissue collected from the biopsy device, a white cassette (black arrow) in which to place target samples, a hemostat (green arrow) to spread apart sample pieces, and a formalin container (*) to send samples to the pathology department. <b>(b)</b> The specimen is routinely imaged to confirm adequate sampling of the target. <b>(c)</b> The specimen radiograph can help determine which specific tissue cores (circles), in this case calcifications, to place in the cassette.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Placing the tissue marker. (a) Scout 2D radiograph shows an area of architectural distortion (circle) to be sampled at biopsy. (b) Photograph taken after adequate sampling was performed shows the tissue marker applicator being inserted into the sheath until it is secure. The plunger (arrow) is then pressed to deploy the marker. (c) DBT image obtained after marker placement shows the marker in the biopsy cavity and a residual area of architectural distortion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig15a.jpeg" height="1869" width="1313" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Placing the tissue marker. <b>(a)</b> Scout 2D radiograph shows an area of architectural distortion (circle) to be sampled at biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Photograph taken after adequate sampling was performed shows the tissue marker applicator being inserted into the sheath until it is secure. The plunger (arrow) is then pressed to deploy the marker. <b>(c)</b> DBT image obtained after marker placement shows the marker in the biopsy cavity and a residual area of architectural distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Placing the tissue marker. (a) Scout 2D radiograph shows an area of architectural distortion (circle) to be sampled at biopsy. (b) Photograph taken after adequate sampling was performed shows the tissue marker applicator being inserted into the sheath until it is secure. The plunger (arrow) is then pressed to deploy the marker. (c) DBT image obtained after marker placement shows the marker in the biopsy cavity and a residual area of architectural distortion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig15b.jpeg" height="1869" width="881" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Placing the tissue marker. <b>(a)</b> Scout 2D radiograph shows an area of architectural distortion (circle) to be sampled at biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Photograph taken after adequate sampling was performed shows the tissue marker applicator being inserted into the sheath until it is secure. The plunger (arrow) is then pressed to deploy the marker. <b>(c)</b> DBT image obtained after marker placement shows the marker in the biopsy cavity and a residual area of architectural distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic" aria-label="Placing the tissue marker. (a) Scout 2D radiograph shows an area of architectural distortion (circle) to be sampled at biopsy. (b) Photograph taken after adequate sampling was performed shows the tissue marker applicator being inserted into the sheath until it is secure. The plunger (arrow) is then pressed to deploy the marker. (c) DBT image obtained after marker placement shows the marker in the biopsy cavity and a residual area of architectural distortion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig15c.jpeg" height="1869" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Placing the tissue marker. <b>(a)</b> Scout 2D radiograph shows an area of architectural distortion (circle) to be sampled at biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Photograph taken after adequate sampling was performed shows the tissue marker applicator being inserted into the sheath until it is secure. The plunger (arrow) is then pressed to deploy the marker. <b>(c)</b> DBT image obtained after marker placement shows the marker in the biopsy cavity and a residual area of architectural distortion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Postbiopsy hematoma. (a) Craniocaudal diagnostic mammogram shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled at biopsy, with no adjacent vasculature. (b) Postbiopsy mediolateral mammogram shows an expanding hematoma (arrow); additional manual compression was applied. (c) Subsequent left breast targeted US image shows a 5-cm hematoma with a pulsatile central vessel (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig16a.jpeg" height="1472" width="1291" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Postbiopsy hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal diagnostic mammogram shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled at biopsy, with no adjacent vasculature. <b>(b)</b> Postbiopsy mediolateral mammogram shows an expanding hematoma (arrow); additional manual compression was applied. <b>(c)</b> Subsequent left breast targeted US image shows a 5-cm hematoma with a pulsatile central vessel (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Postbiopsy hematoma. (a) Craniocaudal diagnostic mammogram shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled at biopsy, with no adjacent vasculature. (b) Postbiopsy mediolateral mammogram shows an expanding hematoma (arrow); additional manual compression was applied. (c) Subsequent left breast targeted US image shows a 5-cm hematoma with a pulsatile central vessel (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig16b.jpeg" height="1472" width="854" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Postbiopsy hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal diagnostic mammogram shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled at biopsy, with no adjacent vasculature. <b>(b)</b> Postbiopsy mediolateral mammogram shows an expanding hematoma (arrow); additional manual compression was applied. <b>(c)</b> Subsequent left breast targeted US image shows a 5-cm hematoma with a pulsatile central vessel (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic" aria-label="Postbiopsy hematoma. (a) Craniocaudal diagnostic mammogram shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled at biopsy, with no adjacent vasculature. (b) Postbiopsy mediolateral mammogram shows an expanding hematoma (arrow); additional manual compression was applied. (c) Subsequent left breast targeted US image shows a 5-cm hematoma with a pulsatile central vessel (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig16c.jpeg" height="1472" width="1563" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Postbiopsy hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal diagnostic mammogram shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled at biopsy, with no adjacent vasculature. <b>(b)</b> Postbiopsy mediolateral mammogram shows an expanding hematoma (arrow); additional manual compression was applied. <b>(c)</b> Subsequent left breast targeted US image shows a 5-cm hematoma with a pulsatile central vessel (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Avoiding vessels. (a) Prebiopsy magnification mediolateral radiograph shows a vessel (arrow) adjacent to calcifications (circle) that will be sampled at biopsy. (b) Mediolateral DBT image before biopsy shows a vessel (arrow) at the needle tip. (c) DBT image after breast rolling shows that the vessel has been displaced to prevent increased bleeding."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig17a.jpeg" height="1319" width="1976" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Avoiding vessels. <b>(a)</b> Prebiopsy magnification mediolateral radiograph shows a vessel (arrow) adjacent to calcifications (circle) that will be sampled at biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Mediolateral DBT image before biopsy shows a vessel (arrow) at the needle tip. <b>(c)</b> DBT image after breast rolling shows that the vessel has been displaced to prevent increased bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Avoiding vessels. (a) Prebiopsy magnification mediolateral radiograph shows a vessel (arrow) adjacent to calcifications (circle) that will be sampled at biopsy. (b) Mediolateral DBT image before biopsy shows a vessel (arrow) at the needle tip. (c) DBT image after breast rolling shows that the vessel has been displaced to prevent increased bleeding."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig17b.jpeg" height="1664" width="1285" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Avoiding vessels. <b>(a)</b> Prebiopsy magnification mediolateral radiograph shows a vessel (arrow) adjacent to calcifications (circle) that will be sampled at biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Mediolateral DBT image before biopsy shows a vessel (arrow) at the needle tip. <b>(c)</b> DBT image after breast rolling shows that the vessel has been displaced to prevent increased bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic" aria-label="Avoiding vessels. (a) Prebiopsy magnification mediolateral radiograph shows a vessel (arrow) adjacent to calcifications (circle) that will be sampled at biopsy. (b) Mediolateral DBT image before biopsy shows a vessel (arrow) at the needle tip. (c) DBT image after breast rolling shows that the vessel has been displaced to prevent increased bleeding."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig17c.jpeg" height="1664" width="1363" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Avoiding vessels. <b>(a)</b> Prebiopsy magnification mediolateral radiograph shows a vessel (arrow) adjacent to calcifications (circle) that will be sampled at biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Mediolateral DBT image before biopsy shows a vessel (arrow) at the needle tip. <b>(c)</b> DBT image after breast rolling shows that the vessel has been displaced to prevent increased bleeding.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Inadequate sampling. (a) Scout DBT radiograph shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled. (b) Radiograph of the initially obtained specimen shows no visible calcifications. (c) Repeat DBT image shows that the calcifications (circle) are lateral to the needle tip (arrow); directional sampling was performed clockwise from the 6- to 12-o’clock positions through 9 o’clock. (d) Radiograph of the second specimen shows the targeted calcifications (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig18a.jpeg" height="1693" width="1147" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Inadequate sampling. <b>(a)</b> Scout DBT radiograph shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled. <b>(b)</b> Radiograph of the initially obtained specimen shows no visible calcifications. <b>(c)</b> Repeat DBT image shows that the calcifications (circle) are lateral to the needle tip (arrow); directional sampling was performed clockwise from the 6- to 12-o’clock positions through 9 o’clock. <b>(d)</b> Radiograph of the second specimen shows the targeted calcifications (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="Inadequate sampling. (a) Scout DBT radiograph shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled. (b) Radiograph of the initially obtained specimen shows no visible calcifications. (c) Repeat DBT image shows that the calcifications (circle) are lateral to the needle tip (arrow); directional sampling was performed clockwise from the 6- to 12-o’clock positions through 9 o’clock. (d) Radiograph of the second specimen shows the targeted calcifications (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig18b.jpeg" height="1693" width="524" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Inadequate sampling. <b>(a)</b> Scout DBT radiograph shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled. <b>(b)</b> Radiograph of the initially obtained specimen shows no visible calcifications. <b>(c)</b> Repeat DBT image shows that the calcifications (circle) are lateral to the needle tip (arrow); directional sampling was performed clockwise from the 6- to 12-o’clock positions through 9 o’clock. <b>(d)</b> Radiograph of the second specimen shows the targeted calcifications (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210017&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic" aria-label="Inadequate sampling. (a) Scout DBT radiograph shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled. (b) Radiograph of the initially obtained specimen shows no visible calcifications. (c) Repeat DBT image shows that the calcifications (circle) are lateral to the needle tip (arrow); directional sampling was performed clockwise from the 6- to 12-o’clock positions through 9 o’clock. (d) Radiograph of the second specimen shows the targeted calcifications (circle)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210017/asset/images/large/rg.2021210017.fig18c.jpeg" height="1693" width="1188" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Inadequate sampling. <b>(a)</b> Scout DBT radiograph shows calcifications (circle) to be sampled. <b>(b)</b> Radiograph of the initially obtained specimen shows no visible calcifications. <b>(c)</b> Repeat DBT image shows that the calcifications (circle) are lateral to the needle tip (arrow); directional sampling was performed clockwise from the 6- to 12-o’clock positions through 9 o’clock. <b>(d)</b> Radiograph of the second specimen shows the targeted calcifications (circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" h